			<tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">I use plugins to achieve metalic effects.  There are long, tedious ways to achieve metallic effects using the built-in filters, but I haven't used them in years.
<br />

<br />

<br />

<br />
Alien Skin's Eye Candy 4000 has a nice &quot;chrome&quot; filter which I use often.
<br />

<br />

<br />

<br />
Flaming Pear's SuperBladePro has a complex interface for creating a wide array of textures ranging from wood, stone, leather, to steel.  I generally only use this for metal if I want a weathered, corroded appearance.
<br />

<br />

<br />

<br />
Sometimes I will mix and match, layering a EyeCandy chrome layer over a SuperBladePro layer with blending modes and opacity settings to get the best of both worlds.  Sometimes I'll even layer two Chrome layers together to get different highlites. 
<br />

<br />

<br />

<br />

<br />

<br />
